<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1925-03-07T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1925-03-07T06:00:00-05:00" n="178" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d178">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">867n.01/421: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Sterling</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1925-03-07T11:00:00+00:00"><hi rend="italic">March 7,
                                        1925—11 a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received March 7—10:45
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>94. The Foreign Office having heard from Sir Esme Howard<note n="14" xml:id="d178fn14">British Ambassador at Washington.</note> that the
                            Palestine mandate treaty<note n="15" xml:id="d178fn15">Convention of
                                Dec. 3, 1924, between the United States and Great Britain, <ref target="frus1924v02#pg_212"><hi rend="italic">Foreign
                                        Relations</hi>, 1924, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p.
                                    212</ref>.</note> has been ratified by the Senate, asks me by an
                            informal communication whether we are ready to proceed to the exchange
                            of ratifications.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Sterling</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>